 Q.   Is there any pressure on Europe as the favourites?   
PABLO LARRAZÃBAL:   I mean, I don't know, I have pressure enough to be nearby my teammates in the team room.   You know, I don't know if we are or not the favourites.   We are tied 0‑0, so we will see on Saturday afternoon who are the champions.   But you know, this weather is tough for us.   We are not 100 percent used to it.   We don't play with this grass every week like they do.   So you know, if someone is up already, obviously Miguel won, but they are 1‑up because they know the grass of the golf course.   
   
 Q.   You guys are so used to playing for yourself, how difficult is it to make an adjustment to play a team sport suddenly for a few weeks and maybe Ryder Cup, to suddenly come together where you are not just worrying about your own game but the strengths of your partner; how difficult is the adjustment?   
GRAEME McDOWELL:   Yeah, like you say, golf is a very individual sport, one of the toughest parts of, say, The Ryder Cup is, is putting pairings together, and getting foursomes pairings more importantly.  
That's why a tournament like this, the EurAsia Cup, to me is something that's very, very important for both The European Tour and the Asian Tour.   Like Miguel alluded to there, this is the main area of growth for the game of golf in the world.   So it's a natural place for The European Tour.   It's obviously a big part of The European Tour to have a Europe versus Asia match is something that our schedule needs from a Ryder Cup point of view.   We need this event to become something very special, something the guys look forward to and something that is part of The Ryder Cup Team building; a chance to put ten guys together, come out here and play against a good team and try some pairings and really enjoy playing team golf.  
It's different.   Like Pablo said, you have extra pressure because you're playing for each other.   You don't want to let your teammates down.  
   
 Q.   What kind of adjustments do you make to your game?   
GRAEME McDOWELL:   Well, alternate‑shot is probably the most difficult format in golf.   You know, there's nothing worse than playing foursomes golf and blowing your partner six‑foot past the hole and say, over to you, buddy.   It's the hardest format in golf.   I won my first‑ever half‑point in Ryder Cup back in 2008 playing with this man in foursomes at Valhalla.   It was a great game, and it was an amazing experience and like I say, I think foursomes is one of the key, key games of The Ryder Cup, and finding guys that can complement each other and play together is a big key, and that's why EurAsia Cup I think is important for The European Team to come together and work on that type of stuff.   
   
 Q.   Have you played this course?   What do you find about the course?   
MIGUEL ANGEL JIMÃNEZ:   The golf course is not very long‑‑ the game is probably from the tee, because the grass, the fairways is very narrow and you can have a lot of flyers, and the greens are not very big.   So it is very important to hit the fairways and to be able to hit those greens.   You hit flyers, it's very difficult.   
GRAEME McDOWELL:   I like the air conditioning in the locker room is nice.   
   
 Q.   The players today, they have such strict fitness regimes and go to the gym; how do you manage to stay on the top of your game?   Do you have a regime besides the cigars?   
MIGUEL ANGEL JIMÃNEZ:   Yes, of course.   You think only drinking wine and cigars you can be 50 years old and competing with these yuck guys?   No Chang.   I also work on the gym and work on myself.   The main thing is that you have to enjoy what are you doing in your life and I love the game.   I love to compete because I'm here.   It's a mix of a lot of things, not only gym, not only the games; it's a mix, and enjoy your life, that's the main thing.  
   
  
  
  
  
  

